This paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category as it deals with channel estimation in wireless communication systems. Additionally, the use of correntropy induced metric (CIM) and maximum correntropy criterion (MCC) are common techniques in information theory. 

The paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it proposes a sparse adaptive filtering algorithm for channel estimation, which involves learning from data. 

The Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-category is also a likely fit as the paper deals with processing signals in wireless communication systems. 

The Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category is a possibility as the paper proposes a novel algorithm for channel estimation, which involves optimization. 

Finally, the Statistical Learning (cs.SI) sub-category is a possibility as the paper deals with sparse channel estimation, which is a common problem in statistical learning.
